<DOCNO> AP880927-0004 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
a neighborhood trying to buck bureaucracy 
middlemen and rising inflation has created chinas first consumer 
food cooperative in 30 years 
the tiantan residential area consumer cooperative in beijing 
opened in april and already has 9000 members who paid 5 yuan 
130 a share for access to fresh and sometimes cheaper 
vegetables milk eggs matches food oils and other consumer goods 
our only purpose is to serve the people said the coops 
general manager yang jingson 
it is run entirely by people living near the landmark temple of 
heaven in southern beijing 
consumer cooperatives existed in the early years after the 
communist government came to power in 1949 but were taken over by 
the state in 1957 when our economy became more developed yang 
said 
the idea has been revived three decades later as china goes 
through the painful process of ending price controls and letting 
the value of most food products be determined by market forces 
prices for many vegetables and other food items have doubled in 
the past year amid an overall inflation rate of around 20 percent 
the reluctance of farmers to grow lowprofit crops difficulties in 
transport and widespread profiteering in scarce commodities have 
added to the price spiral the most serious problem facing the 
chinese economy today 
the tiantan neighborhood committee decided to start the coop 
yang said mainly to eliminate all kinds of troubles happening 
between producers and consumers 
the cooperative has signed contracts with several farm villages 
outside beijing for supply and delivery of cucumbers milk sesame 
oil and other items which are stocked in some of the 40 shops now 
run by the cooperative 
most of the 100 people working for the cooperative are retired 
from regular jobs or unemployed yang said 
zhang xuyuan 69 said she came out of retirement to run a 
little corner shop that sells soft drinks canned goods and fresh 
foods because i wanted something to do 
now she says she works up to 12 hours a day and takes home a 
wage pegged to the shops sales and averaging about 100 yuan 27 
a month on a par with a factory workers salary 
shoppers she said are quite satisfied theyve got no 
quarrels with the cooperative products 
yang said the little groceries barely break even but the 
cooperative is earning good profits from several larger retail 
stores 
he said shareholders should receive dividends larger than 
interest rates on bank savings deposits 
he added that as china switches to a commoditybased economy 
the government permits consumers to have various shopping options 
the coop he said will be a little brother to stateowned 
food shops and will not hurt the free markets that now supply urban 
residents with much of their betterquality if more expensive food 
although elimination of middlemen will mean better prices for 
coop members yang said prices will generally be pegged to those 
in state stores but that holding the line on price rises will be 
tough 
he expressed confidence however that the coop could provide 
good service at reasonable prices and make things a little 
easier for our residents 
 
</TEXT>
