<TEXT>
president pw botha completes 
10 years in power wednesday pressing ahead with policies that have 
disenchanted blacks and whites across south africas political 
spectrum 
not interested in charming his way to popularity botha has 
presented himself as a stern dedicated patriot leading his country 
on a precarious path between outright racism and black majority 
rule 
lately his balancing act has won little praise growing numbers 
of rightwing whites feel he has gone too far in extending power to 
blacks while white liberals and a solid core of blacks believe he 
has fallen woefully short 
the criticisms and increasingly frequent calls for new 
leadership sometimes rankle botha but he is unapologetic 
my attitude is that i am doing what i believe to be right and 
in the interests of the country he recently told a television 
interviewer who sought an assessment of 10 turbulent years 
in his early years in power botha had a broad mandate from 
whites for his twin goals of maintaining stability while moving 
away from rigid apartheid 
the sunday times south africas largest newspaper and a critic 
of the government commented this month mr bothas place in 
history is assured it required courage to lead his people out of 
the culdesac of apartheid even if the final destination of their 
new course remains uncharted 
botha 72 became head of the whiteminority government on sept 
28 1978 when parliament members elected him prime minister over 
more moderate and more conservative rivals 
he had been in the cabinet since 1961 and became defense 
minister in 1966 his first speech as prime minister stressed a 
theme that remains dear to him the paramount importance of 
national security in the face of a purported communistled total 
onslaught 
a year later in one of his most quoted remarks he sounded a 
different theme telling whites we must adapt otherwise we will 
die 
in 1984 botha helped push through a new constitution that 
brought asians and people of mixed race into the previously 
allwhite parliament but continued to exclude blacks one result 
was black anger that ignited two years of nationwide political 
violence 
the constitution abolished the post of prime minister and botha 
became president his critics say he has steadily increased the 
power of the executive branch since then while weakening parliament 
since 1984 botha has been credited with the repeal of several 
of apartheids most hurtful laws including those that banned 
interracial marriages and required blacks to have a permit to be in 
whitesonly areas 
these reforms along with promises of limited powersharing with 
blacks triggered a wave of defections by bothas fellow afrikaners 
from the national party to the extremeright conservative party 
bothas anniversary comes as the national party verges on losing 
support of a majority of whites for the first time since it gained 
power 40 years ago 
the party won 55 percent of the vote in whitesonly general 
elections in may 1987 while 26 percent went to the conservative 
party and 19 percent to liberal candidates 
the conservatives are believed to have gained strength since 
then and could outpoll the national party in nationwide local 
elections oct 26 
many liberals believe botha has gone as far as he is willing to 
go toward substantive reform the president has declared that some 
aspects of apartheid are nonnegotiable he rejects equal voting 
rights for blacks and insists that whites retain segregated 
neighborhoods and schools 
we are forever told that president bothas government has 
chosen the path fo reform and should be given a chance wrote 
black newspaper editor khulu sibiya what chance when they move 
one step forward and three backwards 
botha whose government has detained thousands of black 
activists during a 27monthold state of emergency says most 
blacks view him favorably 
opinion polls suggest otherwise 
this month botha held his first summit meetings in black 
africa he visited malawi a longtime friend of south africa and 
mozambique a longtime adversary 
some critics say botha is more willing to take chances in the 
international arena than at home 
one has to say that pw botha lacks imagination said peter 
soal parliament member for the antiapartheid progressive federal 
party he has failed to deal creatively with black political 
aspirations 
even some of bothas own cabinet ministers feel he should step 
down said soal is there someone with the guts to tell him 
</TEXT>
