<TEXT>
ne win who resigned two months ago 
after 26 years of despotic rule is widely believed to still be the 
top man in burma orchestrating moves to put down the 
antigovernment uprising 
many western diplomats and burmese believe ne win has been 
calling the shots since he stepped down july 23 as chairman of the 
burma socialist program party that has ruled the country for a 
quarter century 
i would say the almost universal perception and opinion among 
burmese is that ne win is still the government of burma a 
rangoonbased diplomat said 
ne win 77 has remained out of public sight since he resigned 
and there is no indisputable evidence he remains the most powerful 
figure 
but observers characterize the men who have led the government 
since he stepped down as longtime associates of ne win who dare 
not make any major move without his assent 
diplomats said military commander gen saw maung visited ne win 
at his home in the plush northern rangoon suburbs around scenic 
inya lake before launching a coup sept 18 that began a harsh 
crackdown on prodemocracy protesters 
the rangoonbased diplomat said a number of other meetings 
have been held at critical times between ne win and top officials 
sein lwin who became head of the party and state to succeed ne 
win in july was a military leader known for his ruthlessness and 
longtime political association with ne win 
when protests against sein lwins authoritarian rule increased 
in august he was replaced by civilian maung maung who served as 
ne wins legal adviser and wrote a flattering book about him called 
burma and general ne win 
tzang yawnghwe an author and son of burmas first president 
described maung maung as one of the few burmese intellectuals who 
sincerely and deeply admired gen ne win 
maung maung was removed from power by saw maung when promises to 
hold the first multiparty elections since 1960 failed to end 
massive antigovernment street demonstrations and a crippling 
general strike 
saw maung who was promoted to armed forces commander in 1985 
is regarded as a hardliner who during most of his 39year army 
career has loyally followed orders from ne win 
ne win didnt raise up a generation of leaders but raised a 
generation of followers to do his bidding a bangkokbased 
diplomat observed 
another diplomat said the three successors are generally viewed 
as absolutely beholden to the charismatic ne win whose 
unquestioned supremacy over the capable wellorganized 186000man 
military since his 1962 coup is seen as the key to his lasting 
power 
the opposition so far has been unable to draw into its fold the 
rankandfile soldiers and their officers who in the past week 
shot and killed largely unarmed peaceful demonstrators and broke 
up dozens of protest centers throughout the nation 
what striking about it is the ruthlessness of his ne wins 
tactics the bangkokbased diplomat said 
japanese burma expert minoru kiryu suggests however that 
events of recent weeks do not follow a ne win scenario since 
the coup leaders abolished virtually all the state organizations 
built up by the military strongman 
ne win first came to prominence as one of burmas thirty 
comrades who played a key role in the fight for independence from 
britain he ended burmas shaky postindependence experiment with 
democracy by leading the 1962 coup 
ne win quickly vowed to lead his country on a neutralist 
egalitarian and moralistic burmese road to socialism 
but inefficiency corruption and black marketeering soon spread 
throughout the system and burma rich in natural resources and once 
the worlds largest exporter of rice is now one of the worlds 
poorest nations 
the failure to oust ne win and his cronies despite the popular 
uprising has led to certainly a tremendous mood of depression and 
disillusionment in the country the rangoonbased diplomat said 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
dan biers is the associated press news editor in 
hong kong and is assisting in coverage of the burma crisis 
</TEXT>
