morton thiokol maker of the rocket 
booster that caused challengers destruction hopes a successful 
launch for discovery will begin an awakening from a 32monthlong 
corporate nightmare 
it will be the final demonstration to our customer nasa and 
the country that solid rocket motors are going to be a reliable 
contributor to future shuttle successes said dick davis vice 
president and assistant general manager of space operations at 
morton thiokols wasatch operations in utah 
less easily dispatched are the specters of an fbi investigation 
lawsuits by frustrated former employees and a plague of rocket 
fuelrelated accidents including an mx missile motor fire that 
killed five employees last december 
the presidential commission that investigated the jan 28 1986 
shuttle disaster found that an oring seal on the right booster 
rocket had stiffened in freezing prelaunch temperatures allowing 
superheated gas to escape and trigger an explosion 
worse the commission learned that several morton thiokol 
engineers had argued the night before that just such a disaster 
could occur but were overruled by superiors who told nasa the 
launch should proceed 
in the relentless glare of the postmortem morton thiokol 
embarked on an exhaustive booster redesign that kept some 3000 
workers busy on the field joints as well as the casetonozzle 
motor joint the nozzle assembly and hundreds of smaller components 
its been a very difficult period said davis i dont 
think any company is ever prepared for the kind of intense scrutiny 
that you get following a tragedy like challenger 
allan j mcdonald a morton thiokol engineer who had argued 
against the challenger launch was made vice president of 
engineering for space operations overseer of the booster redesign 
his guiding principle in the 500 million effort has been 
redundancy multiple seals bolts and clamps to contain the 11 
million pounds of solid fuel that burn in just two minutes 
the national aeronautics and space administration has borne the 
redesign cost and morton thiokol agreed to reap no profit 
engineers have conducted five 20 million fullscale 
testfirings of the redesigned boosters as well as hundreds of 
subscale and component tests a sixth fullscale test is planned 
for december 
with 8000 employees and an annual payroll of 220 million 
morton thiokol inc is utahs largest private employer the 
chicagobased company also produces munitions salt and specialty 
chemicals and manufactures firststage motors for the mx trident 
2 and midgetman strategic missiles and propulsion systems for 
tactical missiles 
