the united states and soviet union have held 
preliminary talks on ways to limit the spread of ballistic missiles 
to third world countries according to an administration official 
us officials had made it known earlier this month that they 
hoped such a meeting could be arranged with soviet officials while 
they visited washington for broader arms control discussions 
the spread of ballistic missiles to such countries as argentina 
brazil and north korea has been a concern of the united states and 
its industrial allies for some time 
the united states and its six major trading partners last year 
agreed to restrict exports of items that could be used to build 
ballistic missiles with a range of more than 180 miles and a 
payload in excess of 1100 pounds 
the allies reiterated their concern about missile proliferation 
among third world nations at a meeting earlier this month in rome 
and it was hoped at that time to enlist soviet involvement 
the state department said the subject was discussed in a meeting 
monday between assistant secretary of state allen holmes and viktor 
p karpov the senior soviet arms control negotiator 
