voting would be the only way for some voters to convey their 
rejection of apartheid 
only candidates who are openly and sincerely committed to the 
complete abolition of apartheid are worthy of christian support 
the letter said 
a similar letter issued by the southern african catholic bishops 
conference said the elections could further entrench apartheid 
the elections will mark the first time south africans of all 
races go to the polls the same day most antiapartheid activists 
oppose participation in segregated local elections as long as the 
black majority is excluded from full participation in national 
elections 
numerous activist clergymen including anglican archbishop 
desmond tutu have defied a stateofemergency regulation 
forbidding calls for an election boycott 
stateofemergency regulations in effect since 1986 restrict 
reporting about unrest security force actions treatment of 
detainees some forms of protest and a range of statements the 
government considers subversive enforcement of the regulations has 
not been comprehensive 
apartheid establishes a racially segregated society in which the 
26 million blacks have no vote in national affairs the 5 million 
whites control the economy and maintain separate districts schools 
and health services 
</TEXT>
