<TEXT>
the environmental protection agency has 
ordered drastic curtailments of highly toxic tinbased marine 
paints banning unsupervised use by pleasure boat owners the 
agency said tuesday 
the regulations carry out a new law requiring a fivefold 
reduction in the release rate of the active ingredient in the 
paints tributyl tin or tbt compounds from most hulls 
the law bans use of the paints on nonaluminum hulls of vessels 
of less than 25 meters or 82 feet in deck length and requires a 
longterm daily average release rate of 4 micrograms per square 
centimeter about 01 thousandths of an ounce per square foot or 
less on other hulls existing paints can release tbt at about 20 
micrograms per square centimeter 
the paints may be sold from inventories until dec 16 and be 
used until next june 16 
sold since the 1960s the nine tbt compounds make the paint last 
much longer than other compounds needed to prevent the growth of 
barnacles and other organisms on hulls 
but their extreme toxicity has led to oyster shell deformities 
in france england and oregon and epa estimates that mussels and 
clams may be killed at concentrations as low as 20 parts per 
trillion a concentration reported for at least 30 us sites 
primarily areas with heavy boating activity 
as it proposed to do before congress stepped in epa said it is 
restricting sale of the paints to applicators certified under state 
pesticide programs use will be limited to those applicators or 
people working under the direct personal supervision of certified 
applicators 
formulators must revise labels to incorporate provisions of the 
new regulations and instructions for proper disposal 
the law gives epa authority to modify the release rate after it 
completes its studies and the agency warned that its action in 
adopting the congressionally mandated rate in its regulations was 
not final and could be changed 
epa said it may have enough data next year to determine 
acceptable limits to human health of tbt ingested in drinking water 
and fish tissues 
data on additional ecological effects worker exposure and 
environmental fate of the compounds are due from manufacturers over 
the next four years 
about 1 million pounds of tbt compounds have been used in some 
624000 gallons of paint sold each year of which about 4 percent 
has gone to paint docks buoys and other gear 
copperbased paints which require painting every year or two 
instead of the sevenyear interval possible with tbt are the chief 
alternative 
</TEXT>
