nations general assembly said the interior department measure 
exceeds his request by 680 million and brings the federal budget 
closer to sequestration under the grammrudman deficit reduction 
act 
this congressional overspending cannot continue if the nation 
is to avoid the uniform acrosstheboard cuts that a sequestration 
inflicts equally on lower priority programs and on the high 
priority programs upon which many americans depend he said 
regarding the congressional moratorium on granting oil and gas 
leases for certain areas of the outer continental shelf the 
president said the congress increased the damaging effects of 
the moratorium by extending it to apply to grants of permits for 
drilling and exploration activities under leases already granted 
for the congress to prohibit the issuance of such permits to 
those who already had obtained leases is unfair reagan said 
the president also said many provisions of the bill reflect a 
growing and disturbing trend on the part of the congress to include 
unconstitutional committee approval or veto requirements in 
appropriations bills 
he said the measure would require for instance the approval of 
congressional committees to change forest service regional 
boundaries to close forest service regional offices or to reduce 
personnel in the indian health service 
in granting authority or making appropriations by law the 
congress may not reserve to its committees approval or veto power 
over the exercise of that authority or the expenditure of those 
appropriations the president said 
since congress has indicated such a special interest in 
these matters he said the administration will consult the 
lawmakers about them 
</TEXT>
