<TEXT>
despite reforms the pentagon is still doing a 
poor job of managing its inventory of millions of stockpiled items 
ranging from aircraft spare parts to food and clothing a senate 
report said tuesday 
the pentagon should reduce the huge and growing volume of items 
it has in its inventory according to the study by the senate 
governmental affairs committee 
the report was the latest in a series of studies by the 
democraticcontrolled panel of how the pentagon manages its huge 
stockpile the studies have been critical of the defense department 
and have recommended management changes 
the studies affect socalled secondary items which include 
spares repair parts supplies food and clothing that stockpile 
is in contrast to principal items like tanks ships and 
airplanes 
there has been a large increase in the secondary item stockpile 
resulting from president reagans defense buildup the secondary 
stockpile which now contains about 46 million different types of 
items is worth 94 billion compared to its 43 billion value in 
1980 
the enormous unprecedented and unsustainable growth in the 
pentagons secondary inventory has simply overwhelmed the 
pentagons depots warehouses and accounting and control 
systems the report said 
the defense departments supply system has been unable to cope 
with the new demands made on it the management of current 
inventories has not kept pace with the pentagons ability to spend 
money on new goods it said 
for example two years ago the army missile command asked army 
officials in europe to return 24 stinger handheld missiles for 
test firing the missile command sought 24 specific missiles but 
service officials in europe were able to find only nine by march 
1987 
finally after searching the armys entire european inventory of 
missiles service officials were finally able to locate the other 
13 
army officials conceded that their policy for recording 
inventory information on small missiles was ambiguous and contained 
multiple and contradictory control requirements the study said 
pentagon officials asked for comment did not immediately 
respond 
however they agreed with the general accounting office last 
spring when the congressional watchdog agency raised similar 
criticisms of the pentagons inventory management defense 
department officials conceded they needed to do better 
the committee recommended a number of changes including a halt 
in the purchase of items not immediately needed and better 
administrative and internal pentagon controls over the vast and 
widely segmented inventories 
one example cited as wasteful spending was the purchase by the 
defense logistics agency of metal bars used to mount flashing red 
lights atop emergency and police vehicles used by the services 
because of an increase in demand the dla bought 4297 of the 
bars in february 1986 but shortly after the purchase the demand 
dropped that means that the dla now has enough of the bars to last 
for the next six years and stocks of the bars are now clogging the 
aisles of a sla warehouse 
the panel also said the pentagon needs to improve security at 
sites where weapons and other potentially dangerous items are 
stored a complaint raised in previous hearings 
for example the panel said its investigators found that 
stinger missiles were stored at various sites in west germany in 
lightweight metal sheds with the word stinger stenciled on the 
sheds side 
</TEXT>
