<TEXT>
aquaculture production in the united states 
which includes fish farming has grown by 20 percent a year since 
1980 the agriculture department said tuesday 
production includes food and nonfood fish shellfish and 
aquatic plants the departments economic research unit said 
domestic production of food fish and shellfish amounted to an 
estimated 700million pounds in 1987 and was worth almost 550 
million at the farm gate compared with 203 million pounds and 191 
million in 1980 the agency said last year nonfood 
aquacultural production included among other items 715 million 
of baitfish and 23 million of tropical fish 
the report by the usda agency was the first in six years when 
aquaculture began to move up as an agricultural enterprise reports 
were issued in 1980 1981 and 1982 they were dropped after that as 
an economy measure 
during the 1980s americans have substantially increased the 
quantity of fish and shellfish in their diets despite the fact that 
seafood prices have risen considerably faster than those for some 
major competing sources of dietary protein the report said 
per capita consumption of all fishery products rose 18 percent 
to 202 pounds in 1987 from an estimated 171 pounds in 1980 
the largest sources of us fishery products are domestic wild 
harvests and imports the report said commercial fishermen landed 
a record 11 billion pounds of fish and shellfish last year with a 
wholesale value of 36 billion an increase of 18 billion pounds 
and 500 million from 1986 
imports were valued at a record 88 billion in 1987 led by 
17 billion worth of fresh and frozen shrimp lobster and tuna 
were next at 600 million and 500 million respectively 
</TEXT>
