the house on tuesday approved a compromise 
spending bill appropriating 148 billion for the operations of the 
federal judiciary and the state commerce and justice departments 
for the fiscal year starting saturday 
the vote was 269141 on the measure worked out by negotiators 
for the house and senate which previously had approved two 
separate bills the senate has to approve the compromise bill 
before it can be sent to the white house for president reagans 
signature 
the total is 761 million or 5 percent more than was approved 
last year but 655 million or 4 percent less than the reagan 
administrations request 
although some agencies received major increases including the 
census bureau which is preparing for the 1990 census the budgets 
of some others were frozen or cut back 
these include the justice departments antitrust division and 
the us parole commission the commerce departments economic 
development administration the minority business development 
agency and the patent and trademark office the state departments 
maintenance program for buildings abroad and the commission on 
civil rights the federal trade commission and the office of the 
us trade representative 
the agencies which are required to absorb a recently approved 
41 percent pay increase likely will face hiring freezes 
furloughs and reductions in force 
the overall bill has a number of provisions unrelated to funding 
the federal communications commission for example is required 
to reverse a recent ruling and prohibit radio stations from 
broadcasting obscene or profane language at any time of the day or 
night the fcc had approved socalled adult broadcasting between 
the hours of midnight and 6 am 
