<TEXT>
farm lawmakers reached a compromise tuesday on 
an agricultural money bill that placed a 770 million ceiling on 
the nations major export subsidy program in the upcoming fiscal 
year 
lawmakers are still adding up the items in the massive money 
bill which covers everything from farm subsidies to food stamps 
but the total was between the 441 billion house level and the 
senates 473 billion 
under the measure produced by a housesenate conference 
committee spending on the export enhancement program would be 
capped at 770 million in the fiscal year starting saturday 
the administration had requested 900 million for the program 
under which major grain companies and other exporters are paid with 
surplus crops to spur exports of american farm products 
established under the wideranging 1985 farm law the program 
has been responsible for stepped up shipments of us wheat and 
feedgrains 
sen thad cochran rmiss had pushed for a larger amount but 
said the level approved would not put too large a crimp in the 
program 
i think this is a strong signal that we are at level of export 
assistance that will ensure that we will be able to sell in the 
international marketplace anything we have available to sell he 
said 
the committee also put a 200 million ceiling on expenditures 
under the targeted export assistance program which supplies aid 
for advertising and other promotion of american agricultural 
products overseas 
the program had been scheduled to increase to 325 million a 
year under the 1985 farm program it has been criticized in the 
house recently for providing taxpayer aid for the products of 
specific companies 
the conferees also adopted a compromise with the administration 
that would defer for one year a cut in the amount that production 
credit associations would have to pay to bolster the financially 
wobbly farm credit system 
production credit associations are local lending institutions 
that are part of the massive borrowerowned system which 
represents the nations largest farm lender the associations were 
required to pay assessments under a federal bailout passed by 
congress in 1986 
the reagan administration monday had called on conferees to drop 
the provision calling for a lowering of the assessment level 
threatening a presidential veto of the entire bill 
