<TEXT>
officials running a police training school 
tuesday defended an exercise session that hospitalized 16 cadets 
including one who required a liver transplant 
the cadets were treated at hospitals beginning sept 19 the 
first day of classes with ailments ranging from exhaustion and 
dehydration to kidney failure 
gary f egan executive director of the massachusetts justice 
training council said no cadet was denied water during the 
training and that activity on the first day was no more strenuous 
than any other groups first day at an academy 
there was strenuous physical activities as there always was 
on that first day but we have found no one that was denied 
water upon request egan said at a news conference 
the most seriously ill cadet timothy shepard 25 a pittsfield 
police trainee collapsed while running on the track and has been 
in a coma for a week 
he received a liver transplant early tuesday at 
presbyterianuniversity hospital in pittsburgh and remained in 
critical condition 
mike purcell of northampton who quit the edward j connelly 
criminal justice training center after one day said recruits were 
required to exercise vigorously and were kept moving with pushups 
and laps if they failed to respond quickly to orders 
we started at 730 am with a formation with our gear our 
jackets boots and other stuff in a duffel bag weighing 50 to 60 
pounds and we had to walk to classes carrying the duffel bag 
above our heads with one arm he said 
we also moved metal lockers and heavy wood furniture from the 
basement up to either the second or third floor of the building 
he said everybody was pushed to the limit before we even got to 
the physical training part 
george f grady the states chief epidemiologist said the 
cadets who became ill at the training facility in agawam suffered 
from dehydration and exhaustion 
law enforcement officials said they would investigate training 
routines at massachusetts police academies 
nearly three dozen police chiefs from western massachusetts have 
asked the state attorney general to have an independent agency 
investigate the academy 
john p mchugh chairman of the training council said the 
council the state attorneys general office and state police would 
investigate training procedures in the academies 
hopefully the councils mission will be to correct this so it 
wont occur in the future mchugh said 
but grady said we feel at this time that the cause of illness 
was a relatively insufficient intake of water relative to the 
amount of exercise they were doing 
the executive office of public safety oversees the council 
which certifies the states 12 police academies egan said that 
stressful situations are often introduced as part of the 
training to see if any of the cadets may react improperly 
wed rather have them do it in the academy than out in the 
streets egan said 
asked if it was the cadets who were at fault for not drinking 
enough water egan replied some of them were unaware of the fact 
that they were doing damage to themselves they had a chance to go 
home every night to rehydrate 
several stricken cadets told reporters that they could not 
comment on their experiences at the training facility without 
permission from their supervisors but one former cadet said the 
training routine was severe and that trainees were allowed only two 
cups of water before shepard collapsed 
ive been through basic training in the army and it was twice 
as bad as that said purcell the doctors told me that if i had 
gone back for a second day i could have suffered permanent kidney 
damage 
a spokesman at the baystate medical center springfield hospital 
said that shepard also suffered kidney problems and several of the 
other cadets received kidney dialysis treatment six remained 
hospitalized 
after cadets were urged to seek medical examinations 21 were 
found to exhibit symptoms from fatigue and nausea to kidney failure 
dr constance lentz of the university of massachusetts in 
amherst said tuesday that she treated three to eight holyoke cadets 
suffering from fatigue and kidney problems after their first day at 
the academy in 1984 
i wish in retrospect that i had pushed harder for them to 
protest the severity of their training she said 
