<TEXT>
a senator has called on his 
congressional colleagues to slow down on investigations the 
probes he said often never end and keep legislators and other 
officials from more useful work 
i have nothing against such investigations per se sen rene 
saguisag said but i dont think that when we were elected last 
year we would be let loose we 200plus members of congress to 
investigate everyone and everybody 
whatever is in the headlines today tomorrow it will be 
investigated 
he added that the communist insurgency continues and crime 
increases because generals and police chiefs spend too much time 
answering questions at congressional hearings 
saguisag made his appeal for a cutback on probes during a 
television talk show discussion with sen juan ponce enrile who 
took the opposite view just hours before the show enrile called 
for yet another investigation the 73rd pending before the 
23member senate 
the bicameral congress reconvened last year for the first time 
since it was abolished in 1972 by the nowdeposed president 
ferdinand e marcos since resuming sessions both houses have 
initiated scores of probes on controversies chiefly brought out by 
manilas freewheeling press 
the probes involve subjects ranging from the countrys 28 
billion foreign debt and alleged corruption to religious cults and 
whether gold bullion is buried under an old spanish fort or if two 
missing bargeloads of rice are really in the bottom of the sea 
in early september when a top player in the philippines 
professional basketball league was benched for no specified reason 
during a championship series congress launched an investigation 
in some cases investigations have made matters worse 
after a recent congressional factfinding trip to the southern 
philippines sen leticia ramos shahani openly accused malaysia of 
annexing six filipino islands her accusation led to calls by other 
legislators and officials for action just short of war 
mrs shahani later apologized however saying she failed to 
verify an allegation made by a naval officer who had misread a 
navigational chart 
saguisag a harvardtrained lawyer complained that in many 
cases the probes fade into oblivion after media interest wanes 
often investigations would never have been started if congressmen 
had bothered to think twice about them he said 
im dumbfounded by the lack of preliminary staff work 
saguisag said 
enrile the lone opposition member of the senate recently 
called for investigations into alleged corruption involving 
relatives of president corazon aquino and the sale of a lot in 
california last year 
just before the tv show he asked for an investigation into what 
a newspaper called a list of economic saboteurs prepared by 
finance secretary vicente jayme which included unidentified 
legislators 
enrile maintained on the show that probes were necessary to help 
legislators gather information to prepare legislation in cases of 
alleged corruption involving presidential relatives he said 
congress should investigate because no one else will 
saguisag said that if investigations were unavoidable 
congressmen should be more restrained in what they say in their 
sessions about other people who might be slandered and have no 
means of redress because congressmen enjoy immunity 
saguisag acknowledged nevertheless that as chairman of the 
senates ethics committee he himself is conducting several probes 
asked by program host luis beltran what punishment congress can 
give erring congressmen saguisag replied that in the 1950s a 
member of the house was suspended for 15 months because he made 
false charges against the president 
i am willing to be suspended for 15 months enrile said i 
can use it for vacation but if i will get suspended for the error 
of information i received i expect that an equal measure will be 
applied to a senator of the ruling coalition who has brought us to 
the brink of war 
that was a reference to mrs shahani and her erroneous charge 
against malaysia 
</TEXT>
