<TEXT>
for a decade in a bucolic corner of 
mississippi the rev herman fountain ran his bethel home for 
children from time to time tales of abuse circulated but nothing 
came of them mississippi is one of six states where such church 
homes are unlicensed and rarely scrutinized but as this summer 
began a boys tale of beatings neglect and imprisonment brought 
state authorities to bethels door and ignited a conflict fueled by 
outrage from both sides gates of hell is the story of these 
children who have been given pseudonyms to protect their 
identities as required by mississippi law of their lives inside 
bethel and of the emotional struggle over their futures and their 
souls this is the first installment of three 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
a wise man feareth and departeth from evil proverbs 
1416 from a sign on a building at the bethel childrens home 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
the time had come patrick was ready he 
would hide and wait and when the moment was right he would blow 
through the gates of hell and never look back 
quietly now quietly he slipped inside the locker and waited 
hardly breathing the other kids at the bethel home for children 
were filing past on their way to church 
patrick opened the locker door to the bicycle by the steps 
carefully now carefully if anyone saw he would be caught and 
thered be more punishment more pain more humiliation 
no more hed had enough for a lifetime 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
kathy prine had just finished stabling her horse when the phone 
rang sunday may 8 it was after 7 pm 
as a child welfare investigator in george county she was used 
to calls at all hours seven days a week it was the sheriffs 
office another runaway from bethel that wasnt unusual the 
baptist church homes 10year history was rife with kids trying to 
escape its rigorous regimen 
prine had dealt with some of bethels children but had never 
seen the operation firsthand because the state does not license 
its churchrun boarding homes and therefore cannot regulate them 
it rarely ventures in 
among those who have some call them hospitals for the soul 
others consider them spiritual torture chambers 
the truth about the bethel home for children was a matter of 
opinion 
in 1980 a runaway brought assault charges against bethels 
founder the rev herman fountain for a beating he received with a 
switch licks fountain called them after a hearing the 
youth court judge removed all the children and directed the church 
to follow certain regulations but the charges were dropped and the 
order was never enforced many of the children were returned to 
bethel 
since then other children had run away and others told stories 
of abuse and neglect but few had been at bethel long enough to be 
credible witnesses the kind whose stories would hold up in court 
now there was patrick 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
he had come to bethel in october 1986 at age 13 a sometime 
truant sent from florida by his mother 
life might have been hard at home but bethel was like boot camp 
with a wrathful god as drill sergeant patricks description was 
the same as those of other children and that of herman fountain 
himself 
each day had a schedule up at 5 am so many minutes in the 
bathroom so many minutes to dress so many to clean the dormitory 
there were prayer sessions morning and evening 
in the summers the children picked beans pulled weeds on the 
churchs 28 acres dug ditches picked up trash and cared for 
bethels menagerie of goats horses ducks and deer sometimes 
crews of children would tear down abandoned buildings including 
some at keesler air force base in biloxi and return with what they 
salvaged to bethel where it would become part of new structures 
they built themselves 
there was no payment for work but plenty of punishment for 
slackers 
in the winters they had bible memorization and school lessons 
came from religious workbooks often children had to erase other 
childrens answers to fill in their own 
like every new bethel charge patrick spent his first month on 
watch under the eye of more trusted child children on watch were 
allowed to speak only to designated individuals it was a way to 
prevent them from planning escapes talking on watch meant sure 
punishment 
</TEXT>
