part of an independent republic bordering the rhine river from 
1870 to 1945 the region passed regularly back and forth between 
german and french hands 
the bicultural history is felt today in nearly every aspect of 
daily life from the bildings on the street to the music on the 
radio even the names of city streets reveal strasbourgs seesaw 
history 
in 1871 avenue napoleon became kaiser wilhelmstrasse after the 
germans moved in that was changed to boulevard de la republique 
after world war i then for some years it was known as adolf hitler 
strasse until it was given its current name avenue charles de 
gaulle when the french reclaimed the city at the end of world war 
ii 
the avenue today is filled with a blitzkrieg of german tourists 
who arrive by the busload in this city of 400000 just two miles 
from the west german border they are outnumbered only by french 
sightseers who stroll through the narrow medieval streets of 
halftimbered houses past outdoor cafes and hidden courtyards and 
over picturesque bridges on the ill river 
many people speak both german and french and older people often 
are fluent in alsatian the regional linguistic hybrid 
the intertwining of cultures has produced a cuisine that melds 
german ingredients and french knowhow to cook up regional dishes 
like choucroute sauerkraut and smoked meat cooked in wine 
kronenbourg beer is brewed here rhine wines in a dry french 
style are produced nearby 
cuisines and languages have blended with ease the regions two 
religions have not unlike most of france which is 80 percent 
roman catholic alsacelorraine is half protestant 
when a protestant girl married a catholic boy here it used to 
be considered a disgrace except for a very few small villages 
its not that way anymore said city councilman gilbert roos 
whose father was a medical officer in the german army in world war 
i and in the french army in world war ii 
roos said the two groups now live in harmony the discord these 
days is within the catholic church itself 
in june a longbrewing dispute between the vatican and catholic 
traditionalists culminated in the excommunication of rebel 
archbishop marcel lefebvre it was the first schism within the 
roman catholic church in more than a century and has led to 
repeated calls by the french hierarchy for unity in the face of the 
challenge posed by lefebvre and his flock 
as he did on a trip to france two years ago pope john paul is 
likely to stress loyalty to rome on this visit which begins at 
strasbourgs massive cathedral a dramatic setting for the popes 
first speech 
built between 1190 and 1489 by master french and rhineland 
craftsmen the pink sandstone cathedral rises 465 feet and was the 
highest building in the christian world until a century ago 
inside is an astronomical clock of ingenious works at 1230 
each afternoon a bell is struck by a figure representing death 
while the 12 apostles receive the blessing of christ and a cock 
beating its wings crows three times in memory of peters denial 
a perpetual calendar on the clock calculates the phases of the 
moon solar eclipses and rising and setting of the sun 
while here the pope also will speak at both the european 
parliament and council of europe 
the presence of these two european institutions has stirred the 
ambitions of some local boosters 
it is not surprising the pope is coming here said roos 
one day we wont be just another beautiful city someday we will 
be the capital of europe 
 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

