<TEXT>
 
still live ecm keith jarrett trio 
 
jazz pianist keith jarrett who unlike many of his 
electronicminded contemporaries still plays only the piano has 
never sounded better than in this twodisc live recording 
communicating intuitively with bassist gary peacock and drummer 
jack dejohnette jarrett combined his signature moody chord 
voicings with sharp improvising in a collection of jazz standards 
for a concert audience in munich west germany 
he took the songs familiar melodies and stretched twisted and 
bent them in fascinating ways the listener is never lost though 
and he ends each journey back at the beginning exhilarated and 
ready for another 
jarretts interpretation of my funny valentine was 
understated and sensitive while when i fall in love became a 
ballad with a bit of an attitude 
come rain or come shine had just the right bluesy edge only 
the song is you a kernhammerstein composition failed to 
achieve a groove that matched its length nearly 17 minutes 
keith jarrett is an intelligent pianist who has done his share 
of experimenting still live with its classic tunes played on 
acoustic piano should give purists plenty to cheer about 
 
barry hanson associated press writer 
 
