david hunt vice chairman of abas retail electronic services 
and bank card division said the increase stemmed from the federal 
tax law which is phasing out credit card interest deductions over 
a fouryear period ending in 1991 
the study released monday also found that overall growth in 
the bank credit card business had slowed because of stiff 
competition from other issuers such as sears and american express 
the survey results reflect the fierce competition among bank 
card issuers said hunt the range of prices and card features 
gives consumers a virtually unlimited number of options 
the number of visa and mastercard cardholders grew by about 9 
percent last year a slowdown in the rate of previous years 
according to hunt visa and mastercard both bankowned credit card 
associations represent 60 percent of the bank credit card market 
weve seen the entrance of significant new competition over 
the last couple of years said hunt who also is executive vice 
president of signet banking corp richmond va 
the report found consumers charged more than 165 billion on 
their bank cards last year an increase of 188 percent for 
mastercard and 123 percent for visa 
the aba report was based on a survey of 1444 cardissuing banks 
selected from a national sample based on asset size and includes 
1987 and first quarter 1988 data on bank card interest rates fees 
marketing and operations 
the number of banks charging the maximum interest rate allowed 
in their states declined to less than onefourth according to 
hunt who attributed the drop to increased market competition 
