<TEXT>
the chicago mercantile exchange and the nations 
largest options clearing house have reached an agreement on new 
rules to ease the strain on the system caused by heavy trading 
officials said 
the agreement between the merc and chicagobased options 
clearing corp announced monday calls for crossmargining on 
certain stock index futures and options accounts 
margins are deposits paid by traders to cover the risk of daily 
losses cross margining allows traders to have credit for trading 
positions that reduce their risk of loss 
under the plan traders who have protected their positions by 
hedging in both markets would have to put up less money for their 
margins 
the practice was recommended by a presidential commission that 
investigated last octobers stock market crash and must be approved 
by the securities and exchange commission and the commodities 
futures trading commission 
officials from the mercantile exchange and options clearing the 
nations largest options clearing house have been working on the 
crossmargining program for about a year 
had crossmargining been permitted during the huge decline in 
the stock market on oct 19 it would have reduced the strain on 
the nations financial system and eased demands for cash on several 
major banks that ran into billions of dollars a day 
